- If \(n\) is even, then after flipping \(n-2\) switches each minute, the number of switches that are on will alternate between even and odd numbers. Since we start with 0 switches on (an even number), after an even number of minutes, the number of switches that are on will still be even. Therefore, it is impossible to have all \(n\) switches on (an even number) after an even number of minutes. Similarly, after an odd number of minutes, the number of switches that are on will be odd, and it is impossible to have all \(n\) switches on (an even number) after an odd number of minutes. Thus, \(E(n, n-2) = \infty\) for even \(n\).
- If \(n\) is odd, then after flipping \(n-2\) switches each minute, the number of switches that are on will alternate between odd and even numbers. Since we start with 0 switches on (an even number), after an odd number of minutes, the number of switches that are on will be odd. Therefore, it is possible to have all \(n\) switches on (an odd number) after an odd number of minutes. The minimum number of minutes required is 3, because after 1 minute, 2 switches are on, after 2 minutes, 4 switches are on, and after 3 minutes, 6 switches are on, and so on. Since \(n\) is odd, after \(n-2\) minutes, \(n-2\) switches will be on, and after \(n-1\) minutes, \(n-1\) switches will be on, and after \(n\) minutes, \(n\) switches will be on. Thus, \(E(n, n-2) = n-1\) for odd \(n\).

